Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Scott Allen Rauch in court with attorney Thomas W. Kurzynski.  Brittany Skye Kachingwe appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Statements made as to Sentencing by both counsel and the Defendant.

Defendant sentenced to serve 45 DAYS in the House of Correction (HOC) with credit for 0 days time served.  Huber privileges under Sec.303.08 Wis. Stats. to apply work, child care, and treatment.  

Court IMPOSED AND STAYED the sentence and placed Defendant on Probation with the State of Wisconsin, Department of Corrections for a period of 6 MONTHS with the following conditions:
*  No new law violations reaching the level of a probable cause finding.
*  Cooperate with agent.
*  Pay the Mandatory DNA fee out of bail on deposit, if any; and the balance due prior to the end of the probationary period.  Failure to pay shall result in a Civil Judgment with tax intercept. Court waives all other costs and surcharges.  Defendant is indigent.
*  Maintain ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.
*  AODA assessment with follow up care and treatment.
*  Random urine screens with no positive results.
*  Restitution set at ZERO.
*  Defendant shall not be in possession of any firearms or weapons during the probationary period.

Received and filed with the court:
*  Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief Form

Defendant Scott Allen Rauch in court with attorney Thomas W. Kurzynski.  Brandon A Wigley appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: LNR
  
Plea hearing proceeded. Negotiations placed on the record and confirmed by defense counsel and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1: 
Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.

Defense requests additional time to obtain information on restitution for defendant to make payments. Case adjourned for sentencing on 11/21/2016 at 08:30 am, branch 45.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for November 21, 2016 at 08:30 am.
